WEBVTT

00:02.450 --> 00:07.317
Adult Dean: Growing up in
the '60s, I was surrounded by
images of the ideal
middle-class, suburban life,

00:07.317 --> 00:09.043
and I wanted nothing more
than to have

00:09.043 --> 00:11.218
my own big, fat slice
of that American pie.

00:11.218 --> 00:12.633
♪♪

00:12.633 --> 00:14.600
Can you blame me?

00:14.600 --> 00:16.878
Those smiling white people
made happiness and prosperity

00:16.878 --> 00:19.122
look so damn appealing.

00:19.122 --> 00:21.918
It only seemed fair --
if other families

00:21.918 --> 00:24.300
got to have these cool,
middle-class experiences,

00:24.300 --> 00:25.680
who said mine couldn't, too?

00:25.680 --> 00:28.062
Hey, Dad.
Can we go to the beach?

00:28.062 --> 00:29.477
Sharks.

00:29.477 --> 00:31.238
My dad. That's who.

00:31.238 --> 00:33.723
Hey, Dad, can we rent
a cabin in the woods?

00:33.723 --> 00:35.173
Bears.

00:35.173 --> 00:37.313
Hey, Dad,
can we get a dog?

00:37.313 --> 00:39.004
Fleas.

00:39.004 --> 00:40.971
But I was not going to
give up that easily.

00:40.971 --> 00:42.939
I was on a mission
to find my own version

00:42.939 --> 00:44.630
of the suburban
middle-class dream,

00:44.630 --> 00:46.667
one my dad couldn't possibly
say no to.

00:46.667 --> 00:48.324
And I got this one
for archery,

00:48.324 --> 00:49.911
and this one
was for canoeing.

00:49.911 --> 00:51.672
What's that one for?
Camping.

00:51.672 --> 00:54.330
We went on this super cool trip
to the state park.

00:54.330 --> 00:56.573
We didn't shower or brush
our teeth for two whole days.

00:56.573 --> 00:58.299
Cool!
Whoa!

00:58.299 --> 01:01.233
Yeah. And I chopped down a tree
with a hatchet by myself.

01:01.233 --> 01:03.028
[ Chuckling ] Oh, man.

01:03.028 --> 01:04.788
The Dixie Scouts. Of course!
It had everything --

01:04.788 --> 01:07.101
the great outdoors,
terrible hygiene,

01:07.101 --> 01:09.621
and the unsupervised use
of a lethal weapon.

01:09.621 --> 01:11.519
Couldn't get more
all-American than that.

01:11.519 --> 01:13.935
Hey, Brad.
Cool uniform.

01:13.935 --> 01:17.594
And it appears the ladies love
a man in uniform.

01:17.594 --> 01:19.217
That clinched it.

01:20.770 --> 01:22.772
Is my sink
done leaking?

01:22.772 --> 01:24.049
Yep.

01:24.049 --> 01:25.395
[ Groans ]

01:25.395 --> 01:27.363
Third time's
the charm.

01:27.363 --> 01:28.743
I think you mean
the fifth.
[ Door closes ]

01:28.743 --> 01:30.193
Hey, Dad.

01:31.884 --> 01:34.301
Can I join my friend Brad's
Dixie Scout troop?

01:34.301 --> 01:35.647
The Dixie Scouts?

01:35.647 --> 01:37.787
So you want to join
the white troop?

01:37.787 --> 01:40.065
Or as I call them,
the junior Klan.

01:40.065 --> 01:42.205
No, but, Dad,
it's not like that.

01:42.205 --> 01:44.380
Brad's father
is the Scoutmaster.

01:44.380 --> 01:47.279
I'm sorry,
did you say Scoutmaster?

01:47.279 --> 01:49.592
The man in charge
is called "master"?

01:49.592 --> 01:51.490
Listen to yourself,
son.

01:51.490 --> 01:53.423
But, Dad, all my other friends
are doing it.

01:53.423 --> 01:55.011
Yeah, your white friends.
I'm not letting you

01:55.011 --> 01:56.461
join in with those
East Montgomery boys.

01:56.461 --> 01:58.325
Well,
what's the harm in it, Bill?

01:58.325 --> 02:00.603
Well, for starters,
I don't like

02:00.603 --> 02:02.294
how the white Scouts
stole all their rituals

02:02.294 --> 02:03.985
from African
tribal rites of passage.

02:03.985 --> 02:05.918
My dad was of the opinion
that if there was

02:05.918 --> 02:08.162
something of value
in American culture,

02:08.162 --> 02:10.509
it was definitely stolen
from Black people.

02:10.509 --> 02:11.890
[ "Ed Sullivan Show" playing]

02:11.890 --> 02:14.064
Elvis Presley? Ha!

02:14.064 --> 02:16.619
Everything he does,
Big Mama Thornton did first --

02:16.619 --> 02:17.861
except better.

02:17.861 --> 02:20.140
Coca-Cola?
[ Scoffs ] Please.

02:20.140 --> 02:22.176
They'd be nowhere
if Africans hadn't

02:22.176 --> 02:23.867
domesticated the kola nut.
[ Chuckles ]

02:23.867 --> 02:25.352
Santa Claus?

02:25.352 --> 02:27.423
You know the real Saint Nicholas
was a black Moor.

02:27.423 --> 02:28.907
Are you sure about that,
Bill?

02:28.907 --> 02:30.426
I thought the Scouts

02:30.426 --> 02:31.944
got their rituals from
the Native Americans.

02:31.944 --> 02:33.532
And where do you think
they got it from?

02:33.532 --> 02:35.085
I shouldn't have been surprised
that my Dad

02:35.085 --> 02:36.777
didn't want me joining
Brad's troop.

02:36.777 --> 02:38.572
Like a lot of men
from his generation,

02:38.572 --> 02:40.712
he didn't think we needed
to mix with white people

02:40.712 --> 02:42.610
to have a better life.

02:42.610 --> 02:45.337
But that didn't change the fact
that I really wanted this.

02:45.337 --> 02:48.547
Lucky for me, my mom was there
to save the day.

02:48.547 --> 02:50.756
Well,
you want to be a Scout,

02:50.756 --> 02:53.207
you can join the troop
your brother belonged to.

02:53.207 --> 02:55.105
That's right.
We got a perfectly good troop

02:55.105 --> 02:57.107
right in our own neighborhood --
a Blacktroop.

02:57.107 --> 02:58.419
I forgot
all about it.

02:58.419 --> 03:00.283
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah, I'm not surprised.

03:00.283 --> 03:02.665
You were on the road
with your band back then,

03:02.665 --> 03:04.632
and I used to take Bruce
to all his meetings.

03:04.632 --> 03:06.013
Well,
I'm here now,

03:06.013 --> 03:07.325
so I'll take Dean,
get him signed up.

03:07.325 --> 03:08.705
You don't
have to worry

03:08.705 --> 03:09.982
your pretty little head
about a thing.

03:13.365 --> 03:15.712
Ask for Deacon Loren
at the church.

03:15.712 --> 03:17.127
He's the troop leader.

03:17.127 --> 03:18.819
Right.

03:18.819 --> 03:22.650
Nowyou don't have to worry
about one little thing.

03:22.650 --> 03:25.205
[ Water dripping ]

03:25.205 --> 03:26.482
Let's go, Dean.

03:27.586 --> 03:29.692
[ Door opens ]

03:29.692 --> 03:30.796
♪ Oh, oh, oh

03:30.796 --> 03:31.797
♪ And I know

03:31.797 --> 03:33.661
♪ Ohh

03:33.661 --> 03:35.698
♪ Through the highs
and the lows ♪

03:35.698 --> 03:39.011
♪ I'mma find my way home

03:40.565 --> 03:41.738
Sorry, men.

03:41.945 --> 03:45.880
Troop 24 is no more.
Bill: How come?
We had to
shut it down

03:45.880 --> 03:49.194
when the older boys got drafted
to Vietnam to fight.

03:49.194 --> 03:51.334
Guess I did too good a job
teaching those boys

03:51.334 --> 03:53.233
how to run through the woods
and shoot. [ Chuckles ]

03:53.233 --> 03:54.510
Well,
my friend Cory

03:54.510 --> 03:56.477
and a few others
would like to be Scouts.

03:56.477 --> 03:58.548
Maybe we could
start it up again?

03:58.548 --> 04:00.170
No, not with me.

04:00.170 --> 04:03.070
I'm too old to be sleeping
out there on that hard ground,

04:03.070 --> 04:05.935
and eating all of those
weenies and beans out of a can

04:05.935 --> 04:07.661
gave me the gout.

04:07.661 --> 04:09.007
Well, son, we tried.

04:09.007 --> 04:10.974
Dad,
you could do it!
Wait, what?

04:10.974 --> 04:13.114
Yeah, you could be
the Scoutmast--

04:13.114 --> 04:14.392
Scout leader.

04:14.392 --> 04:16.014
You already know
a lot about it,

04:16.014 --> 04:18.982
like how the Scouts stole
all their ideas from Africa.

04:18.982 --> 04:20.605
Is that so,
Bill?

04:20.605 --> 04:22.089
I didn't know that,

04:22.089 --> 04:24.574
and I was a Scout
for 40 years.

04:24.574 --> 04:26.438
True, I'm acquainted
with the history,

04:26.438 --> 04:29.096
but you know how busy I am
with the college and the band.

04:29.096 --> 04:30.960
Don't worry.
You'll figure it out.

04:30.960 --> 04:32.513
You're good
at everything.

04:33.963 --> 04:37.311
Welcome to the Scouts,
Bill. [ Chuckles ]

04:37.311 --> 04:41.419
♪♪

04:41.419 --> 04:42.799
Look, Ma.

04:42.799 --> 04:44.801
Bruce's old uniform
fits like a glove.

04:44.801 --> 04:47.217
Well, it fit about as well
as Bruce's old baseball glove,

04:47.217 --> 04:49.185
which I had to attach
to my arm with duct tape

04:49.185 --> 04:50.531
to keep from falling off.

04:50.531 --> 04:52.222
Mm,
it looks good,

04:52.222 --> 04:54.604
but it's gonna look even better
after I take it in.

04:54.604 --> 04:57.331
Or cut it in half.
[ Chuckles ]

04:57.331 --> 04:59.816
Can't wait to fill
this baby up with merit badges.

04:59.816 --> 05:02.094
So which one
should we do first, Dad?

05:02.094 --> 05:03.441
"We"?

05:03.441 --> 05:05.546
Yeah, Dad's taking over
as troop leader.

05:05.546 --> 05:07.962
You?
Yeah, me.

05:07.962 --> 05:10.102
Where are you gonna find
the time to run a Scout troop?

05:10.102 --> 05:11.621
Well,
I thought maybe

05:11.621 --> 05:13.865
you could help me out
with the paperwork...

05:13.865 --> 05:15.729
and making snacks...

05:15.729 --> 05:18.456
and maybe lead a few meetings
if I have band practice.

05:18.456 --> 05:21.148
Where am Igonna find the time
for you to run a Scout troop?

05:21.148 --> 05:24.358
Looks like somebody's
not getting her Kissing badge.

05:24.358 --> 05:25.808
Dad's gonna be
a great leader.

05:25.808 --> 05:28.466
He's smart.
He can figure out anything.

05:28.466 --> 05:30.640
Oh, you're right
about that.

05:30.640 --> 05:33.229
Your dad is the smartest man
I ever met.

05:34.575 --> 05:36.059
And what I don't know

05:36.059 --> 05:38.614
is all explained right here
in the book.

05:38.614 --> 05:41.030
I couldn't wait for
my first troop meeting,

05:41.030 --> 05:42.721
and we had a great turnout.

05:42.721 --> 05:44.930
My dad had a full slate
of activities planned.

05:44.930 --> 05:47.277
You all ready to
get these merit badges?

05:47.277 --> 05:48.555
Yes!
Yes!
Yes!
Yes!

05:48.555 --> 05:49.625
Let's have some fun.

05:49.625 --> 05:51.972
♪♪

05:51.972 --> 05:54.043
Keep stacking
that wood, son.

05:54.043 --> 05:55.631
♪♪

05:55.631 --> 05:57.564
How's that leak coming?

05:57.564 --> 05:58.944
Just need to put in
the washer, Mr. Williams.

05:58.944 --> 06:00.498
Excellent.

06:00.498 --> 06:03.397
You're one step closer
to getting that Plumbing badge.

06:03.397 --> 06:05.226
I finished
trimming the bushes.

06:05.226 --> 06:06.711
Good work,
Norman.

06:06.711 --> 06:08.368
Now clear the weeds
out of that flower bed

06:08.368 --> 06:10.059
and you'll have yourself
a Gardening badge.

06:10.059 --> 06:12.233
[ Door opens ]

06:12.233 --> 06:13.752
Oh, man.
[ Door closes ]

06:13.752 --> 06:15.098
We are never getting

06:15.098 --> 06:17.411
the stinky-boy smell
out of this house.

06:17.411 --> 06:19.309
Bill, why is there
a young man

06:19.309 --> 06:20.897
painting
our front door?

06:20.897 --> 06:23.037
He's working hard to earn
his Home Repairs merit badge.

06:23.037 --> 06:24.384
You sure
he's not just

06:24.384 --> 06:25.695
checking items
off your Chore Chart?

06:25.695 --> 06:27.179
Ooh, is there
a Laundry badge?

06:27.179 --> 06:29.078
'Cause I don't feel like
doing my chores, either.

06:29.078 --> 06:31.494
Lillian, merit badges...

06:31.494 --> 06:33.738
"Encourage boys
to try out new activities

06:33.738 --> 06:35.325
that may result
in new skills."

06:35.325 --> 06:36.568
I'm sure
that is not

06:36.568 --> 06:38.294
what these little boys
signed up for.

06:38.294 --> 06:40.227
Yeah, Dean said we'd go out
camping and canoeing,

06:40.227 --> 06:42.505
not digging up
other folks' weeds.

06:42.505 --> 06:44.196
Whoa. [ Chuckling ]
Whoa, whoa.

06:44.196 --> 06:46.406
Looks like somebody doesn't want
his Good Citizen badge.

06:47.924 --> 06:49.201
[ Door opens, closes ]

06:49.201 --> 06:51.203
Coach Long:
Hey, Bill.

06:51.203 --> 06:53.585
Come to get Cory.
How's it going?

06:53.585 --> 06:55.898
Ah, you know.
Just over here, men being men.

06:55.898 --> 06:57.244
Alright, now.
[ Both laugh ]

06:57.244 --> 06:58.866
What's up, Dad?
Hey, Mr. Williams,

06:58.866 --> 07:00.350
I'm almost done
baking those cookies.

07:00.350 --> 07:01.938
Now, I remembered
not to use walnuts,

07:01.938 --> 07:03.492
'cause you said it makes
your tummy hurt, right?

07:05.632 --> 07:07.219
You know what, Cory?

07:07.219 --> 07:09.152
I'm just gonna go ahead
and give you that Cooking badge.

07:09.152 --> 07:11.154
And First Aid, too. You could
have just saved my life.

07:11.154 --> 07:12.501
Congratulations, son.
Thank you.

07:12.501 --> 07:14.364
Hey, Bill.

07:14.364 --> 07:18.196
These boys need to be
outside, in nature --

07:18.196 --> 07:22.303
hiking, fishing,
sleeping under the stars

07:22.303 --> 07:24.029
like I did
when I was a Scout.

07:24.029 --> 07:25.548
-Yeah!
-Yeah!
-Yeah!

07:25.548 --> 07:27.654
Hey, Dad,
you could take us camping.

07:27.654 --> 07:30.173
Well, I wouldn't want to
step on Bill's toes,

07:30.173 --> 07:31.554
but if you need my help --
or rather, my expertise...

07:31.554 --> 07:32.831
Dean:
He doesn't.

07:32.831 --> 07:35.696
He can take us,
right, Dad?

07:35.696 --> 07:37.629
Of course, son.

07:37.629 --> 07:41.012
[ Laughs ]
Bill Williams.

07:41.012 --> 07:42.531
What you know
about camping?

07:42.531 --> 07:43.980
It's just like going on the road
with my band,

07:43.980 --> 07:45.395
except
more marshmallows,

07:45.395 --> 07:47.087
but if you want to
spend time with your boy,

07:47.087 --> 07:48.813
I guess it'd be okay
if you came along

07:48.813 --> 07:50.055
as my assistant.

07:51.194 --> 07:55.475
Well, I -- I see it
as a co-leader situation.

07:55.475 --> 07:56.821
Ah, let's not get
hung up on titles.

07:56.821 --> 07:58.167
We're doing this
for the boys, right?

07:58.167 --> 08:00.341
Of course.
Titles are just words.

08:00.341 --> 08:01.791
Just words.

08:01.791 --> 08:04.449
Like, uh --
"Eagle Scout."

08:05.968 --> 08:09.454
"1/16 Cherokee."

08:09.454 --> 08:11.042
Just words.

08:11.042 --> 08:12.906
♪♪

08:12.906 --> 08:15.633
Just words.

08:15.633 --> 08:17.427
♪♪

08:22.294 --> 08:27.127
Spending a weekend in the woods
with a bunch of 12-year-olds
was definitely not
my dad's idea of a good time,

08:27.127 --> 08:29.578
but there was no way
he was gonna let
Coach Long show him up.

08:29.578 --> 08:31.303
So before our trip,

08:31.303 --> 08:33.271
he broke the bank at
the sporting goods store.

08:33.271 --> 08:35.376
The man came to play.
Uh, Bill?

08:35.376 --> 08:37.275
What -- What -- What you doing
with all that stuff?

08:38.379 --> 08:39.967
Now, you know I could
survive for a week

08:39.967 --> 08:41.762
with just a knife,
a canteen,

08:41.762 --> 08:43.039
and two sticks
to rub together.

08:43.039 --> 08:44.524
Well,
you enjoy your sticks.

08:44.524 --> 08:46.111
I believe that if
you're gonna do something,

08:46.111 --> 08:47.354
you should do it
in style.

08:48.700 --> 08:51.358
This tent had all
the bells and whistles --

08:51.358 --> 08:53.429
literally, it had a bell.

08:53.429 --> 08:55.500
Not sure why.
Maybe to scare away bears.

08:55.500 --> 08:58.192
Anyway, it was amazing, and I
couldn't wait to put it up.

08:59.780 --> 09:02.990
I think we put A-23
where C-27 should go,

09:02.990 --> 09:04.371
and where's B-26?

09:04.371 --> 09:05.786
Be cool.

09:05.786 --> 09:07.236
It's just
letters and numbers.

09:07.236 --> 09:08.582
We'll figure it out.

09:08.582 --> 09:10.204
Y'all still
working on that, huh?

09:10.204 --> 09:11.758
Now,
don't you worry, Bill.

09:11.758 --> 09:13.760
If it rains, you can put
that pretty box over your head.

09:13.760 --> 09:15.313
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah, well...

09:15.313 --> 09:17.211
if you hear a bear
in the middle of the night,

09:17.211 --> 09:19.282
don't come running to
ring my bell.

09:19.282 --> 09:20.974
[ No sound ]

09:20.974 --> 09:23.321
It's at a frequency
only bears can hear.

09:23.321 --> 09:24.564
Yeah, bears don't
work like that.

09:26.151 --> 09:27.808
Who wants to go
chop some firewood up?

09:27.808 --> 09:29.879
All: Me!
Come on, y'all.

09:29.879 --> 09:33.262
♪♪

09:33.262 --> 09:35.609
I'll stay and help
with the tent.

09:35.609 --> 09:37.507
Thank you, son.

09:37.507 --> 09:39.820
I refuse to believe
that this grinning idiot

09:39.820 --> 09:41.650
is smarter than me.

09:41.650 --> 09:42.961
[ Chuckles ]

09:42.961 --> 09:44.998
♪♪

09:44.998 --> 09:47.725
I think that's supposed to
be a skylight.

09:47.725 --> 09:49.071
Well,
it's a door now.

09:49.071 --> 09:51.073
Hey, Dean.
You won't believe it, man.

09:51.073 --> 09:52.661
We were chopping down trees,
right?

09:52.661 --> 09:54.628
And a copperhead
came up from under the log!

09:54.628 --> 09:56.492
Then Mr. Long cut it in half
with the hatchet!

09:56.492 --> 09:59.564
But, listen, the head
was still wiggling.

09:59.564 --> 10:02.153
Then a hawk flew down,
grabbed it,

10:02.153 --> 10:03.741
and carried it away.

10:03.741 --> 10:05.121
If it wasn't
for my dad,

10:05.121 --> 10:06.847
we'd all be dead
from that snake.

10:06.847 --> 10:08.849
And Norman would have been
carried off by the hawk.

10:08.849 --> 10:10.333
[ Chuckles ]

10:10.333 --> 10:13.026
Well, uh, the boys
are exaggerating a bit,

10:13.026 --> 10:14.786
but, uh, I did
work up an appetite

10:14.786 --> 10:16.616
saving all these lives.

10:16.616 --> 10:18.618
[ Laughs ] You know,
some of y'all start a fire.

10:18.618 --> 10:20.205
And the rest of y'all,
sharpen up some sticks

10:20.205 --> 10:21.655
so we can roast some hot dogs.
Come on.

10:21.655 --> 10:23.105
Actually, I know you
told me to get hot dogs,

10:23.105 --> 10:26.004
but I did
a lot better than that.

10:28.110 --> 10:31.527
Freeze-dried
beef stroganoff.

10:31.527 --> 10:33.943
What you feeding us?

10:33.943 --> 10:35.980
Beanies and weenies would have
been a whole lot easier.

10:35.980 --> 10:37.775
Cliff, this is the food
of the future.

10:37.775 --> 10:40.053
The salesman told me
this is what the astronauts use.

10:40.053 --> 10:41.675
All we got to do is
add hot water

10:41.675 --> 10:43.643
and we'll be eating
like kings.

10:46.024 --> 10:54.792
♪♪

10:54.792 --> 10:57.277
♪♪

10:57.277 --> 10:59.037
Come on, guys.

10:59.037 --> 11:00.487
If you
close your eyes,

11:00.487 --> 11:02.765
it's just like eating at
a fancy restaurant in...

11:02.765 --> 11:04.940
whatever country
beef stroganoff comes from.

11:04.940 --> 11:06.976
In that moment,
all I could think about

11:06.976 --> 11:10.635
was what my mom and sister were
having for dinner back home.

11:10.635 --> 11:12.119
Ooh. [ Laughs ]

11:12.119 --> 11:13.569
Mama, no.

11:13.569 --> 11:15.398
I couldn't possibly
have one more piece

11:15.398 --> 11:17.400
of Dean's
favorite cornbread.

11:17.400 --> 11:18.919
Not after
I ate two helpings

11:18.919 --> 11:20.610
of Dean's favorite short ribs!
[ Laughs ]

11:20.610 --> 11:22.785
Girl, well, I hope
you saved some room

11:22.785 --> 11:26.202
for a big piece
of coconut cake.

11:26.202 --> 11:27.445
Mmm!

11:27.445 --> 11:29.274
It's Dean's favorite.

11:29.274 --> 11:30.655
[ Both laugh ]

11:32.726 --> 11:34.348
[ Playing "Reveille" ]

11:34.348 --> 11:37.006
At 6:00 a.m.,
Dad decided to wake us up

11:37.006 --> 11:39.250
with a Scout bugle call
that he told us

11:39.250 --> 11:43.081
was a tradition stolen from the
Matabele warriors of Zimbabwe.

11:43.081 --> 11:44.496
[ Clattering ]

11:44.496 --> 11:47.465
[ "Reveille" continues ]

11:47.465 --> 11:49.018
Alright, men,
grab your notebooks,

11:49.018 --> 11:50.848
'cause I want you
to explore the area

11:50.848 --> 11:52.263
and identify
native plants

11:52.263 --> 11:53.851
so you can earn
your Nature badges.

11:53.851 --> 11:55.473
Oh, man.
Oh, man.

11:55.473 --> 11:57.026
Or I saw on the map
there's a crystal-clear lake

11:57.026 --> 11:59.442
with a swimming dock
not too far from here.

11:59.442 --> 12:01.893
Who wants to get their Hiking
badge andtheir Swimming badge?

12:01.893 --> 12:03.653
-Yes!
-Yeah!
-Alright!

12:03.653 --> 12:05.897
Okay, now we're talking.

12:05.897 --> 12:15.907
♪♪

12:15.907 --> 12:18.082
♪♪

12:18.082 --> 12:20.360
Walking sticks?
Seriously?

12:20.360 --> 12:23.363
That salesman clearly
worked on commission.

12:23.363 --> 12:25.365
Hey, you sure you know
where you're going?

12:25.365 --> 12:26.918
We're almost there.

12:26.918 --> 12:28.368
Let me see.

12:28.368 --> 12:30.232
Wait, wait, wait,
wait, wait.

12:31.302 --> 12:33.235
We been off this map
at least a mile.

12:33.235 --> 12:34.892
Impossible.

12:34.892 --> 12:36.721
My lensatic compass tells me
the lake is just up ahead.

12:36.721 --> 12:38.412
Well,
my 1/16 Cherokee blood

12:38.412 --> 12:40.035
tells me
it's back that way.

12:40.035 --> 12:42.209
Are you still spewing that BS
about being part Indian?

12:42.209 --> 12:43.763
I didn't believe you
in third grade

12:43.763 --> 12:45.765
when you made it rain,
and I don't believe you now.

12:45.765 --> 12:47.111
Let's go, son.

12:50.217 --> 12:52.772
[ Birds chirping ]

12:54.359 --> 12:55.913
Almost there.

12:55.913 --> 12:58.294
You said that
20 minutes ago.

12:58.294 --> 13:01.573
Look, I don't care
about the lake anymore.

13:01.573 --> 13:05.025
Can we please just
go back to the campsite?

13:05.025 --> 13:06.820
[ Breathing heavily ]

13:06.820 --> 13:09.512
Fine.
Uh, let me see here.

13:09.512 --> 13:11.687
Admit it --
you're lost!

13:11.687 --> 13:14.828
You have no idea
where we are.

13:14.828 --> 13:17.003
[ Laughter ]

13:17.003 --> 13:19.833
I know
exactly where we are.

13:21.801 --> 13:24.873
[ Indistinct conversations ]

13:24.873 --> 13:26.944
See ya, Lisa.
Bye.

13:26.944 --> 13:28.324
It was nice
meeting you.
Alright.
Good meeting you, Sharon.

13:28.324 --> 13:30.154
Norman: Dean,
where you been, man?

13:30.154 --> 13:31.672
We ran into
these Pixie Scouts,

13:31.672 --> 13:33.260
and they were
really nice.
Yeah.

13:33.260 --> 13:35.262
Cory: One of them didn't have
nobody to talk to,

13:35.262 --> 13:36.539
so I told her
about you.

13:36.539 --> 13:37.851
She wanted
to meet you.

13:37.851 --> 13:40.405
She was wearing a two-piece.
[ Chuckles ]

13:40.405 --> 13:42.511
Alright,
it's getting late, men.

13:42.511 --> 13:43.926
Let's go ahead and head
back to the campsite.

13:43.926 --> 13:46.687
But I didn't get
a chance to swim!

13:46.687 --> 13:49.242
I don't think I've ever been
so angry at my dad.

13:49.242 --> 13:52.245
I knew I shouldn't let it out,
but I couldn't help myself,

13:52.245 --> 13:54.212
so I turned to him
and summoned up

13:54.212 --> 13:56.663
all the 12-year-old eloquence
I could muster.

13:56.663 --> 13:58.665
This stinks!
You stink!

13:58.665 --> 14:00.287
You ruined this trip
for me

14:00.287 --> 14:02.462
because you don't know
what you're doing!

14:02.462 --> 14:04.844
You shoulda just let
Coach Long be the leader!

14:04.844 --> 14:07.191
I stood there,
waiting for my dad to whoop me

14:07.191 --> 14:09.365
for being so fresh
or drown me in the lake --

14:09.365 --> 14:11.851
Wait a minute. Nobody brought
that hatchet, did they?

14:11.851 --> 14:14.439
There's no telling
what this man might do.

14:17.132 --> 14:19.962
But he did nothing.

14:22.792 --> 14:25.174
Coach Long is right.

14:27.142 --> 14:30.455
It'll be dark soon.
We should head on back.

14:30.455 --> 14:32.285
You lead the way, Cliff.

14:32.285 --> 14:42.260
♪♪

14:42.260 --> 14:52.132
♪♪

14:58.794 --> 15:02.763
I could tell my dad
was feeling terrible about
what I said at the lake.

15:02.763 --> 15:05.076
I was feeling
pretty lousy myself,

15:05.076 --> 15:07.907
and he obviously needed my help
putting up that tent.

15:07.907 --> 15:10.426
But you know what?
I was cooking a marshmallow,

15:10.426 --> 15:13.153
and those things go
from brown to black real quick.

15:13.153 --> 15:14.672
[ Breathes sharply ]

15:14.672 --> 15:17.364
It looks like your father
could use a hand.

15:17.364 --> 15:18.607
It's not my fault

15:18.607 --> 15:20.471
he doesn't know
what he's doing.

15:20.471 --> 15:22.128
He's really bad
at this.

15:22.128 --> 15:23.508
Bad?

15:23.508 --> 15:25.476
[ Laughing ]
He's the worst.

15:25.476 --> 15:28.513
[ Chuckles ]
Always has been.

15:28.513 --> 15:32.103
Now, when we were
around your age,

15:32.103 --> 15:34.519
a bunch of us
would go out into the woods,

15:34.519 --> 15:35.935
and your father
would stay home

15:35.935 --> 15:37.626
and practice
his saxophone.

15:38.661 --> 15:40.525
And he would yell at us,

15:40.525 --> 15:42.596
"Y'all can waste your time
chasing those squirrels,

15:42.596 --> 15:44.322
'cause I'm gonna stay home
and practice

15:44.322 --> 15:47.291
so I can play at the Blue Note
in New York City."

15:47.291 --> 15:49.362
And I'll be damned
if he didn't play there

15:49.362 --> 15:51.122
before
we graduated college.

15:52.192 --> 15:55.195
[ Chuckles ]
And I'll be honest --

15:55.195 --> 15:57.542
I couldn't believe
when I heard

15:57.542 --> 15:59.613
he volunteered to be
the troop leader.

15:59.613 --> 16:01.891
Then why'd he do it?

16:01.891 --> 16:04.170
Well, if I had
to take a guess,

16:04.170 --> 16:05.447
um...

16:05.447 --> 16:07.207
he wanted his son
to do something

16:07.207 --> 16:09.589
that was important
to him,

16:09.589 --> 16:14.870
and if that meant
looking a little foolish...

16:14.870 --> 16:19.185
well...he was man enough
to let it happen.

16:19.185 --> 16:21.256
♪♪

16:21.256 --> 16:23.913
[ Chuckles ]
[ Distant laughter ]

16:23.913 --> 16:25.432
Boy, how many times
I told y'all

16:25.432 --> 16:27.400
about playing catch
with the hatchet?!

16:27.400 --> 16:29.367
Hold up.

16:29.367 --> 16:32.129
♪♪

16:32.129 --> 16:34.303
When you're 12,
it's hard to process

16:34.303 --> 16:35.787
the first time you realize

16:35.787 --> 16:38.031
your dad isn't good
at everything.

16:38.031 --> 16:40.758
Or in the case of my son,
when he was 8.

16:40.758 --> 16:43.036
[ Scoffs]
Stupid "John Madden Football."

16:43.036 --> 16:44.865
Like that proves anything.

16:44.865 --> 16:46.971
♪♪

16:46.971 --> 16:48.248
[ Insects chirping ]

16:48.248 --> 16:50.457
♪♪

16:50.457 --> 16:51.976
[ Sighs ]

16:51.976 --> 16:56.153
♪♪

16:56.153 --> 16:57.637
[ Book thumps ]

16:57.637 --> 17:00.053
[ Sighs ]

17:00.053 --> 17:02.124
[ Chirping continues ]

17:04.713 --> 17:13.894
♪♪

17:13.894 --> 17:16.311
There were so many things
I wanted to say to my dad

17:16.311 --> 17:18.658
in that moment --
that it was hard to realize

17:18.658 --> 17:20.970
he wasn't the perfect man
I thought he was.

17:20.970 --> 17:22.524
That I was ashamed of the way

17:22.524 --> 17:25.009
I embarrassed him
back at the lake.

17:25.009 --> 17:26.769
That I was grateful
he was willing to

17:26.769 --> 17:29.358
leave his comfort zone
and do something he hated

17:29.358 --> 17:31.705
so I could do something
I loved.

17:31.705 --> 17:34.743
All these thoughts
swirled around in my head,

17:34.743 --> 17:36.572
until finally, I said...

17:36.572 --> 17:38.885
Dad...

17:38.885 --> 17:41.163
I haven't BM'd
in two days.

17:41.163 --> 17:42.958
Is that
a bad thing?

17:45.167 --> 17:46.686
I think you'll live.

17:46.686 --> 17:48.998
Just don't
tell your mother

17:48.998 --> 17:51.380
or you'll be gulping down
castor oil.

17:51.380 --> 17:54.280
That stuff is almost as nasty
as my stroganoff.

17:54.280 --> 17:55.557
[ Thunder rumbles ]

17:55.557 --> 17:57.214
Oh, y'all see
that lightning?

17:57.214 --> 17:58.456
Mnh-mnh.

17:58.456 --> 17:59.699
Grab your things
and get to the car.

17:59.699 --> 18:01.045
[ Gear clattering ]

18:01.045 --> 18:02.391
We do not
play with God!

18:02.391 --> 18:04.807
Come on!

18:04.807 --> 18:07.845
Come on, now!

18:07.845 --> 18:10.089
[ Thunder rumbling ]

18:11.538 --> 18:13.575
[ Tent poles clattering ]

18:13.575 --> 18:16.336
[ Thunder crashes ]

18:16.336 --> 18:19.477
♪♪

18:19.477 --> 18:23.930
Well, men, it looks like
it's not letting up.

18:23.930 --> 18:27.485
Now we can't earn
any more badges.

18:27.485 --> 18:29.694
You know,
there's one more badge

18:29.694 --> 18:31.489
I remember seeing in the book
that we can still get

18:31.489 --> 18:33.491
before your parents
expect you home.

18:33.491 --> 18:35.355
[ Thunder crashes ]

18:35.355 --> 18:37.978
[ Jazz music playing ]

18:37.978 --> 18:47.988
♪♪

18:47.988 --> 18:57.998
♪♪

18:57.998 --> 19:00.518
♪♪

19:00.518 --> 19:01.864
You hear that?

19:01.864 --> 19:03.487
The bass player
lays down a melody,

19:03.487 --> 19:04.971
and the cat on the piano
responds.

19:04.971 --> 19:06.421
It's called "antiphony."

19:06.421 --> 19:08.216
Straight from
traditional African music.

19:08.216 --> 19:10.114
Thanks to my dad's
quick thinking

19:10.114 --> 19:12.461
and a $5 bill he slipped to
the maître d',

19:12.461 --> 19:15.568
that was the night we all got
our Music Appreciation badges.

19:15.568 --> 19:17.121
Who's ready
for another round?

19:17.121 --> 19:18.260
Me!
Me!
Me!
Me!

19:18.260 --> 19:19.330
It was also the night
we ordered

19:19.330 --> 19:20.780
our first drinks
from a bar.

19:21.988 --> 19:23.921
There's no alcohol
in a Roy Rogers,

19:23.921 --> 19:25.302
but we didn't know that.

19:25.302 --> 19:27.338
We were convinced
we were wasted.

19:27.338 --> 19:29.651
Maybe it was all that
cigarette smoke.

19:29.651 --> 19:31.135
[ Cheers and applause ]

19:31.135 --> 19:33.620
Or maybe it was because

19:33.620 --> 19:35.622
none of us had BM'd
in two days.

19:35.622 --> 19:38.487
Ladies and gentleman,
I see a familiar face out there.

19:38.487 --> 19:40.144
If y'all
make enough noise,

19:40.144 --> 19:42.353
maybe we can convince
Mr. Bill Williams

19:42.353 --> 19:44.459
to come and join us
for a number!

19:44.459 --> 19:46.771
[ Cheers and applause ]
Yeah!

19:48.256 --> 19:50.844
Yeah!

19:53.813 --> 19:55.366
Go, Mr. Williams!
[ Chuckles ]

19:55.366 --> 19:57.851
[ Blowing soundlessly ]

19:57.851 --> 20:00.613
[ Cheers and applause continue ]

20:01.855 --> 20:04.272
[ Music begins ]

20:04.272 --> 20:13.660
♪♪

20:13.660 --> 20:15.800
This was also the night
I realized that

20:15.800 --> 20:18.078
my slice of
the middle-class American dream

20:18.078 --> 20:20.702
might not look like
other people's...

20:20.702 --> 20:24.430
but I had a cool cat
for a father,

20:24.430 --> 20:29.987
a man who would do just about
anything to make me happy...

20:29.987 --> 20:32.127
and that was enough.

20:32.127 --> 20:35.855
♪♪

20:37.891 --> 20:40.929
-- Captions by VITAC --
